column20: Spoke with family regarding patient's decline in health. Was placing a FaceTime call to a patient's daughter so that she could see him and tell him she loved him and say her goodbyes. Patient was having a very difficult time breathing at that point and used every bit of energy he had to attempt to speak to his daughter.
Was placing another FaceTime call to a patient's brother after informing him that the patient was declining and would likely not recover.
Was trying to get organized after being pulled to a new floor that I wasn't originally scheduled for.

Was assessing a COVID patient who required a lot of supportive equipment in the room. The rooms now have fans with filters in the windows to make them negative pressure and sit on the bedside table, which takes away from the already limited amount of "clean" space I have to place things I need to do my work. The patient was very difficult to move as he was non responsive at the time, and all of the extra equipment in the small room made it very difficult to maneuver around the room.
Some Doctors rushing to get off of the unit, my feeling like I can?t get all of my concerns for my patient addressed.

Mentally, physically, and emotionally drained before noon. My uniform and PPE saturated from sweat. Having to FaceTime family of a declining barely responsive patient is a horrible feeling but I?m glad I could at least give that to their family. Today was just one unfortunate event after another. Not a good day.

Was placing a new IV in an 8 week old patient. The previous nurse left the pt with a bad IV and no supplies on this particular floor for the infant (diapers, formula, 24g IV catheters). Had to grab supplies from another department. This was not the normal pediatric floor; it was moved due to the influx of COVID patients.

Was discussing with 7nay/o patient at LENGTH about why it was unsafe for him to get out of bed and attempt to walk around with a tibia/fibula fracture, and with no assistive devices as well. The patient was restless, not used to being stuck in bed, and very impatient for the surgeon to make rounds.
Was missing a medication for a patient

From 11am on, I was informing pts family of patient?s poor and declining status and did call them via Facetime so that they could see him and say what they needed to before saying goodbye to a husband and father they had not seen in a month due to COVID. It was a very difficult experience to see the family hurting and hear them crying and in so much dispair. Shortly after the patient was pronounced by the MD. And we began postmortem care and protocol.

Received a new admit at the same time that I needed to transport my patient to surgery. I was required to transport the patient to the surgery floor myself due to it being the weekend and surgery having limited staff on the weekend.
Reassessing a COVID patient, noted his declining status, lower respiratory rate, fingertips becoming cyanotic, extremities colder, O2 sats dropping. Patient was a DNR

Was trying to get a CBG on a patient and the glucometer ( a new upgrade we have had for approx 1 year) would not scan the patient's wristband and would also not give me the option to manually type in the patient's ID number. This was a COVID patient and I was dressed in full gear, sweating for 3na mins in the patient's room. I had to call another nurse to bring me another machine, which took more time, and after that the new machine would not register the patient's blood sample so I then had to call for more strips, as I had only brought in a small number of them due to the patient's COVID status and not wanting to contaminate the entire bottle.
